<table>
  <tr> 
    <td>Cell1</td>
    <td>Cell2</td>
  </tr>
  <tr> 
    <td>Cell3</td>
    <td>Cell4</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>Rows (tr) are nested inside tables (table) and cells (td for table data) are nested inside rows.<br>
td elements within the same row are displayed on the same line, one after the other: they're inline elements.</p>
<h2>Borders</h2>
<p>Borders can be added to tables, rows and cells with the style attribute.</p>
<table style="border:solid">
<!--adding style="border:solid" to the table tag only adds an outer border-->
  <tr> 
    <td style="border:solid">Cell1</td>
<!--each individual cell has to have a style="border:solid" for it to have a border-->
    <td>Cell2</td>
  </tr>
  <tr> 
    <td>Cell3</td>
    <td>Cell4</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<h2>Table headers</h2>
<p>Tables usually include headers. A header is a special row at the top of the table used to label each column.<br>

You can create header cells with the</p>
<h3>Examples</h3>
<table>
  <tr>
    <th>Name</th><th>Age</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>James</td>
    <td>21</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Anna</td>
    <td>34</td>
  </tr>
<table>
<h3>Colspan and rowspan: Merging cells</h3>
<p>You can make cells that take up multiple rows and/or columns, using the attributes colspan and rowspan. This is called merging cells.<br>

<em>colspan</em> is for the number of columns a cell should span.<br>

<em>rowspan</em> is for the number of rows a cell should span.</p>
<table>
  <tr>
    <th>Month</th>
    <th>Budget($)</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>January</td>
    <td>50000</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>February</td>
    <td>40000</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td colspan="2">Sum: 90000</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<table>
  <tr>
    <th>Month</th>
    <th>Budget($)</th>
    <th>Savings($)</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>January</td>
    <td>500</td>
    <td rowspan="2">150</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>February</td>
    <td>400</td>
  </tr>
</table>

